Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

05/09/22 - Court Reviewed - Defendant is now in compliance with WCS and the matter can be removed from the 05/09/22 calendar. ep

Clerk received and e-mail from Attorney Murray @ 12:48 pm. today, stating his client represented to him that he had made a payment of $100 to WCS toward his outstanding GPS fees, and inquiring if that was sufficeint to remove the BBH scheduled for Monday, 05/09/22 @ 10:30 am.  

However, the clerk contacted WCS @ 1:37 pm. and spoke with John to confirm if payment was made - and John confirmed that no payment was made at their office or WCS in Milwaukee.  

Attorney Murray was notified that the hearing would remain on and that the defendant has not made any payment toward his outstanding balance.  Atty. Murray stated he would contact his client.  
Attorney Murray also informed the clerk he was unable to appear for Monday's hearing, but would let his client know his appearance is mandatory for Monday's hearing.
